---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "1-3 Month Baby Development: The Fourth Trimester",
  "description": "Months 1–3 development data: social smiles, sleep consolidation, feeding amounts, and what's normal vs. a red flag.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "AgeExpectations"
  }
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much should a 1-3 month old sleep?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Total sleep is 14–17 hours per 24 hours. Night stretches lengthen to 3–5 hours by 2–3 months. Naps remain irregular — expect 3–5 per day. A circadian rhythm begins emerging around 6–8 weeks."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much formula does a 2-month-old need?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Formula-fed babies typically consume 4–5 oz per feeding, 6–8 times per day, totaling roughly 24–32 oz in 24 hours. Breastfed babies nurse 8–10 times per day; output remains the best adequacy check."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When do babies smile on purpose?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Social smiles — smiles in response to a face or voice, not gas — typically emerge between 6 and 8 weeks. By 3 months most babies smile readily and vocalize ('coo') in return to interaction."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is it normal for a 2-month-old to not sleep through the night?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Sleeping through the night (5+ hour stretch) is not expected until 3–6 months at the earliest, and many babies don't do it until later. Waking to feed 2–3 times per night at 2 months is completely typical."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does my baby spit up so much?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Gastroesophageal reflux is common in the first months — the lower esophageal sphincter is immature. Most spit-up is effortless and not painful ('happy spitters'). Concern arises with poor weight gain, arching in pain, or projectile vomiting."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="1-3 Months: Baby Development, Sleep & Feeding" description="Months 1–3 development data: social smiles, sleep consolidation, feeding amounts, and what's normal vs. a red flag." schema={schema} faqSchema={faqSchema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>1–3 Month Baby Development: The Fourth Trimester</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 1–3 months · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/1-3-months/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/1-3-months/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/1-3-months/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/1-3-months/feeding/">Feeding</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Months 1–3 are the "fourth trimester." Your baby is completing the neurological development that couldn't finish in utero. Crying peaks around 6 weeks, then declines. The first social smile lands somewhere around 6–8 weeks — and that's the reward for everything before it.</p>

      <h2>Physical Development</h2>
      <p>Motor control is still largely reflexive but becoming more intentional:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Head control:</strong> Briefly lifts head during tummy time by 1 month; holds it for several seconds by 3 months</li>
        <li><strong>Movement:</strong> Limb movements become smoother and less jerky</li>
        <li><strong>Hands:</strong> Opens and closes fists, brings hands to mouth intentionally</li>
        <li><strong>Kicking:</strong> Vigorous, alternating leg kicks when on back</li>
        <li><strong>Tracking:</strong> Follows a moving object 180° by 3 months</li>
        <li><strong>Grasp:</strong> Reflexive palmar grasp present; voluntary grasping begins around 3 months</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Cognitive Development</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Visual preference:</strong> Strongly prefers faces over objects; drawn to high-contrast patterns</li>
        <li><strong>Recognition:</strong> Recognizes primary caregivers' faces and voices by 2–3 months</li>
        <li><strong>Cause and effect:</strong> Beginning to understand that actions produce responses (e.g., crying brings caregiver)</li>
        <li><strong>Habituation:</strong> Looks away from a repeated stimulus — an early sign of memory</li>
        <li><strong>Vocal response:</strong> Stops activity briefly to listen to a new sound</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Social & Emotional</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Social smile:</strong> Emerges 6–8 weeks; one of the clearest early developmental markers</li>
        <li><strong>Cooing:</strong> Vowel sounds ("ooh," "aah") begin around 6–8 weeks</li>
        <li><strong>Calming to voice:</strong> Settles in response to a familiar caregiver's voice</li>
        <li><strong>Gazing:</strong> Sustained eye contact during feeding and interaction</li>
        <li><strong>Attachment:</strong> Preferential response to primary caregivers over strangers is forming</li>
        <li><strong>Crying differentiation:</strong> Caregivers start to distinguish hunger, tiredness, and pain cries</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Sleep Patterns</h2>
      <p>Sleep is consolidating but is not yet reliably patterned:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Total sleep:</strong> 14–17 hours per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Night stretches:</strong> 3–5 hours by 2–3 months; some babies reach 5–6 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Naps:</strong> 3–5 per day, typically 30–90 minutes each, irregular timing</li>
        <li><strong>Circadian emergence:</strong> Day/night differentiation begins around 6–8 weeks</li>
        <li><strong>Wake windows:</strong> 45–90 minutes between sleep periods; overtired babies fight sleep</li>
        <li><strong>Safe sleep:</strong> Back, firm flat surface, no loose bedding — every sleep, every time</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Feeding Schedule & Amounts</h2>
      <p>Hunger drives the schedule at this age — clock-watching is less reliable than cue-watching:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Breastfed frequency:</strong> Every 2–3 hours, 8–10 feeds per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Formula frequency:</strong> Every 3–4 hours, 6–8 feeds per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Formula amount:</strong> ~4–5 oz per feeding (total ~24–32 oz/day)</li>
        <li><strong>Growth spurts:</strong> Expect increased hunger around 3 weeks, 6 weeks, and 3 months</li>
        <li><strong>Hunger cues:</strong> Rooting, hand-to-mouth, fussing before crying</li>
        <li><strong>Fullness cues:</strong> Turning head away, relaxed hands, falling asleep at breast/bottle</li>
        <li><strong>Weight gain:</strong> Expect ~5–7 oz per week (1–3 months)</li>
        <li><strong>No solids:</strong> Exclusive breast milk or formula until at least 4–6 months (AAP recommends 6 months)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Crying & Soothing</h2>
      <p>Crying peaks at 6 weeks — this is biologically normal across cultures:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Peak duration:</strong> Up to 3–5 hours of crying per day at 6 weeks</li>
        <li><strong>Decline:</strong> Crying decreases significantly by 3–4 months</li>
        <li><strong>Evening cluster:</strong> Fussiest period is typically late afternoon to evening</li>
        <li><strong>Effective soothing:</strong> Swaddling, white noise, rocking/swaying, sucking (pacifier or feeding)</li>
        <li><strong>Colic:</strong> Defined as crying &gt;3 hours/day, &gt;3 days/week, for &gt;3 weeks in an otherwise healthy baby</li>
        <li><strong>Shaken baby risk:</strong> Frustration with crying is the leading cause of abusive head trauma — put baby down safely and step away if overwhelmed</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Diaper Output</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wet diapers:</strong> 6+ per day; confirms adequate fluid intake</li>
        <li><strong>Stool frequency:</strong> Highly variable — from multiple times per day to once every several days, both normal in breastfed infants</li>
        <li><strong>Stool color:</strong> Yellow, tan, or green seedy stools are normal; no blood or white</li>
        <li><strong>Urine color:</strong> Pale yellow; dark or strong-smelling suggests inadequate intake</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tummy Time</h2>
      <p>Tummy time builds the strength needed for rolling and crawling:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Goal:</strong> Work toward 30 minutes total per day, broken into short sessions</li>
        <li><strong>Starting amount:</strong> 2–3 minutes per session, 3–5 times per day</li>
        <li><strong>When:</strong> When awake and supervised only — never for sleep</li>
        <li><strong>Position:</strong> Flat floor; can use rolled towel under chest for support</li>
        <li><strong>If baby hates it:</strong> Try chest-to-chest on a reclined parent, or tummy over your lap</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Safe Sleep</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Always place on back — every sleep</li>
        <li>Firm, flat sleep surface (crib, bassinet, or play yard)</li>
        <li>Room-share without bed-sharing for at least 6 months (AAP)</li>
        <li>No loose items: no blankets, pillows, bumpers, or soft toys</li>
        <li>Avoid inclined sleepers, swings, or car seats for unsupervised sleep</li>
        <li>Offer a pacifier at sleep onset (reduces SIDS risk; don't force it)</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Common Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My 2-month-old wakes every 2 hours at night. Is something wrong?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">No. Night waking every 2–3 hours is developmentally appropriate at 2 months. Most babies don't produce enough melatonin for consolidated sleep until 3–4 months. Biological norm, not a problem to fix.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">When should I start a sleep schedule?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Rigid schedules don't work before 3–4 months — the circadian system isn't ready. A loose feed–wake–sleep routine can help from around 6–8 weeks. Watch wake windows (45–90 min) instead of the clock.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My baby only sleeps when held. What do I do?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Common and developmentally normal at this age. Contact napping is not a habit that permanently damages sleep. If you need hands-free time, a carrier/wrap is a practical solution. Independent sleep skills can be gently shaped starting around 4 months.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Is it normal for a 6-week-old to spit up after every feeding?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Frequent spit-up (gastroesophageal reflux) is very common at this age. "Happy spitters" gain weight normally and aren't distressed. Concern flags: poor weight gain, forceful projectile vomiting, or apparent pain with feeds.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Can I let my 3-month-old sleep on their stomach if they roll over?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">At 3 months, babies cannot reliably roll both directions. Always place on back. Once a baby can roll from back to front AND front to back independently, you don't need to reposition them during sleep.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="red-flags">
        <h3>When to Contact Your Pediatrician</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>No social smile by 3 months</li>
          <li>Doesn't track a moving object with eyes</li>
          <li>Doesn't respond to loud sounds</li>
          <li>Seems very stiff (spasticity) or very floppy (hypotonia)</li>
          <li>Doesn't bring hands to mouth</li>
          <li>Poor weight gain or weight loss</li>
          <li>Fewer than 6 wet diapers per day</li>
          <li>Fever ≥100.4°F (38°C) — call immediately under 3 months</li>
          <li>Projectile vomiting or blood in stool</li>
          <li>Difficulty breathing or persistent blue color around lips</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
